We begin by recalling the Purcell‐enhanced emission rate into the cavity mode including both spatial overlap $S$ and frequency detuning $\Delta = \omega_a - \omega_c$. On resonance and at the antinode one has:
$$F_P^{\text{max}}=\frac{3Q(\lambda_c/n)^3}{4\pi^2V}$$
For a detuning $\Delta$ and spatial factor $S$, this becomes:
$$
F_P(S,\omega_a) = S \frac{F_P^{\text{max}}}{1+4Q^2\left(\frac{\omega_a-\omega_c}{\omega_c}\right)^2} = S \frac{F_P^{\text{max}}}{1+4Q^2\frac{\Delta^2}{\omega_c^2}}
$$
The decay rate into the cavity mode is then:
$$
\Gamma_c = \Gamma_0 F_P(S,\omega_a) = \Gamma_0 S \frac{F_P^{\text{max}}}{1+4Q^2\frac{\Delta^2}{\omega_c^2}}
$$
The sum of decay rates into all other channels is:
$$
\Gamma_{\text{other}}=\Gamma_0+\Gamma_{nr}
$$
The total decay rate is the sum of the cavity decay rate and all other rates:
$$
\Gamma_{\text{tot}}=\Gamma_c+\Gamma_{\text{other}}
= \Gamma_0 S \frac{F_P^{\text{max}}}{1+4Q^2\frac{\Delta^2}{\omega_c^2}}
+\Gamma_0+\Gamma_{nr}
$$
The quantum efficiency $\beta$ is the ratio of the cavity decay rate to the total decay rate:
$$
\beta=\frac{\Gamma_c}{\Gamma_{\text{tot}}}
= \frac{\Gamma_0 S \frac{F_P^{\text{max}}}{1+4Q^2\frac{\Delta^2}{\omega_c^2}}}
{\Gamma_0 S \frac{F_P^{\text{max}}}{1+4Q^2\frac{\Delta^2}{\omega_c^2}}+\Gamma_0+\Gamma_{nr}}
$$
To simplify, we divide the numerator and denominator by $\Gamma_0$ and let $D = 1+4Q^2\frac{\Delta^2}{\omega_c^2}$:
$$
\beta
=\frac{\frac{S F_P^{\text{max}}}{D}}
{\frac{S F_P^{\text{max}}}{D}+1+\frac{\Gamma_{nr}}{\Gamma_0}}
=\frac{S F_P^{\text{max}}}
{S F_P^{\text{max}}+D\left(1+\frac{\Gamma_{nr}}{\Gamma_0}\right)}
=\frac{F_P^{\text{max}}S}
{F_P^{\text{max}}S+\left(1+\frac{\Gamma_{nr}}{\Gamma_0}\right)\left(1+4Q^2\frac{(\omega_a-\omega_c)^2}{\omega_c^2}\right)}
$$

1. The spontaneous emission rate into a specific cavity mode $m$ is given by:
$$
\Gamma_m = C \cdot \omega_m \sin^2\left(\frac{m\pi z_0}{L}\right)
\frac{\left(\frac{\kappa}{2}\right)^2}
{(\omega_a-\omega_m)^2+\left(\frac{\kappa}{2}\right)^2}
$$
2. The branching ratio $\mathcal{R}$ is the ratio of the rates for $m=1$ and $m=2$:
$$
\mathcal{R} = \frac{\Gamma_1}{\Gamma_2}
=\frac{C \cdot \omega_1 \cdot \sin^2\left(\frac{\pi z_0}{L}\right) \cdot \frac{(\frac{\kappa}{2})^2}{(\omega_a-\omega_1)^2+(\frac{\kappa}{2})^2}}
{C \cdot \omega_2 \cdot \sin^2\left(\frac{2\pi z_0}{L}\right) \cdot \frac{(\frac{\kappa}{2})^2}{(\omega_a-\omega_2)^2+(\frac{\kappa}{2})^2}}
$$
3. We cancel the common factors $C$ and $(\kappa/2)^2$ to simplify the expression:
$$
\mathcal{R}
=\frac{\omega_1}{\omega_2}
\frac{\sin^2\left(\frac{\pi z_0}{L}\right)}{\sin^2\left(\frac{2\pi z_0}{L}\right)}
\frac{(\omega_a-\omega_2)^2+\left(\frac{\kappa}{2}\right)^2}
{(\omega_a-\omega_1)^2+\left(\frac{\kappa}{2}\right)^2}
$$
4. We use the given relations $\omega_2=2\omega_1$ and $\omega_a=\omega_1+\Delta$. The frequency difference terms become:
$$
\omega_a-\omega_1=\Delta
$$
$$
\omega_a-\omega_2=(\omega_1+\Delta)-2\omega_1=\Delta-\omega_1
$$
5. Substituting these into the expression for $\mathcal{R}$:
$$
\mathcal{R}
=\frac{1}{2}
\frac{\sin^2\left(\frac{\pi z_0}{L}\right)}
{\sin^2\left(\frac{2\pi z_0}{L}\right)}
\frac{(\Delta-\omega_1)^2+\left(\frac{\kappa}{2}\right)^2}
{\Delta^2+\left(\frac{\kappa}{2}\right)^2}
$$
